DCFS DESIGN
===========

Living document. Records what we have discussed and decided, and what is
still open. Update when decisions are made or revisited.


Vision
------

A traditional turn-based roguelike, heavily influenced by DCSS.

Graphics: semi-topdown 3d perspective, 90s aesthetic — low poly, flat
shading, simple low-res textures (Alone in the Dark, 1992).

Online: every game is single player, but played against a server.
Community features are a core goal: spectating other players' games,
tournaments, leaderboards. Cheating must be impossible by construction:
the server owns all game state and the client only ever sees what the
server has told it. A client can at most know what a human spectator
could know.

Networking is NOT implemented first. But the code is structured around
it from day one: running locally means running a local server inside the
game process that talks to the client by passing messages directly
instead of through a socket.


DECIDED: client / server / protocol split
-----------------------------------------

    src/game/
        protocol/    message definitions, shared ids/enums, ser/deser
        server/      authoritative simulation (headless)
        client/      presentation: rendering, input, UI, animation
        game_main.c  local bootstrap: wires client + local server

Layering, enforced by meson include_directories (same mechanism that
hides vulkan from game_lib today):

    protocol -> core
    server   -> core, protocol          (NO engine, NO renderer headers)
    client   -> core, protocol, engine

The server library not being able to even include a renderer header is
the moat. It also means a standalone headless server binary later is
just: core + protocol + server + a network main.

The server is the game. Dungeon generation, the turn scheduler, AI,
FOV, combat resolution, item logic, RNG — all server, and the server
is always the authority. The client folds the server's message stream
into its own view of the world, draws it, and predicts ahead of the
server where it can (see prediction section) — but it only ever works
from information the server has already sent it.

"Common" code is deliberately small: protocol messages, shared ids
(terrain/monster/item types), static display-data tables (id ->
name/model/color — public knowledge, nothing hidden in them), and
pure rule predicates needed for prediction (is this terrain walkable,
...) that operate only on visible state — shared so client prediction
and server resolution cannot drift. Nothing beyond that: sharing
logic that touches non-visible state is exactly how hidden-state
leaks happen.


DECIDED: message flow
---------------------

Client -> server: commands (player intent). Discrete and small:
move dir, attack, use item, descend stairs, ... Turn-based, so low
rate and no timing sensitivity.

Server -> client: two kinds.

  - snapshot: complete visible-state dump. Sent on game start, and
    later on reconnect and spectator join.
  - events: ordered incremental stream. entity moved / took damage /
    died, cell became visible, stat change, ...

Events are semantic game facts, never text and never raw state blobs:
"entity E hit you for 3". The client renders the animation AND
composes the message-log line from the same event. The server never
sends anything the client can derive itself.

The client's authoritative view is a pure function of (snapshot +
events); prediction is an overlay on top of it that server events
confirm or correct, never a second source of truth. The pure-function
property gives us, for free:

  - spectating  = attach a second consumer to the same event stream
  - replays     = record the stream to disk, play it back
  - reconnect   = snapshot + resume stream

Turn model: DCSS-style energy system, server-side. The server is
reactive: it waits for a player command, then advances the world until
the player can act again, emitting events in order. No real-time tick.
The server never waits for client animation; the client buffers events
and plays them at its own pace (and can fast-forward when the queue is
deep, like DCSS does).

Hidden information: FOV is computed server-side; the client is only
sent cells and entities the player can currently see. Map memory
("I've seen this corridor before") is tracked per-player on the server
and sent as part of snapshot/events, so the client stays trivially dumb
and reconnect/spectate get correct memory for free.


DECIDED: local server, same thread
----------------------------------

Locally the server runs in-process on the main thread, pumped once per
frame: drain pending commands, run the simulation, emit events. Turn-
based simulation work is bursty and cheap, so this is fine, and it
keeps debugging deterministic and stack traces whole. Dungeon gen may
hitch a frame; acceptable for now.

Because client and server only talk through the transport, moving the
server to a thread or another machine later changes neither client nor
server code — only which transport is plugged in.


DECIDED: structs across the boundary, serialization only at the edge
--------------------------------------------------------------------

Messages are defined in protocol/ as plain C structs tagged by a
message type enum. Client and server always produce and consume these
structs directly. Serialization/deserialization is the network
layer's job alone: the future socket transport converts struct <->
bytes at the edge. The local in-process server passes structs
straight through and never runs any ser/deser.

The constraint this puts on message structs so the network layer can
be added later without touching them: flat POD, fixed layout, counted
inline arrays for variable-length content (inventory listings, ...),
and NEVER pointers — not into server state, not into client state.
A message is self-contained; receivers copy out what they keep.

Protocol carries a version number from day one. Single-digit cost,
saves grief the moment a real server exists.


DECIDED: client-side prediction (deliberate departure from DCSS)
----------------------------------------------------------------

DCSS online feels unresponsive; we will not copy that. The client
predicts whatever it can from knowledge it legitimately has, so input
feels instant even when the server is remote:

  - movement: the client knows the terrain it has seen and the
    entities it can see, so a legal-looking move starts instantly
    (step + animation) without waiting for the server.
  - inventory: contents are part of the player's knowledge and the
    server keeps the client's copy current, so opening and browsing
    it is pure client-side UI — no round trip at all. Only acting
    (use / drop / wield) sends a command.

The server stays authoritative. Commands carry a sequence number and
authoritative events reference the command that caused them, so the
client verifies each prediction against the server's resolution and
corrects (snaps) when it guessed wrong — e.g. the move was blocked by
something invisible.

Prediction changes nothing for anti-cheat: it runs only on
information the server already sent. Rules that prediction needs must
match the server exactly, which is why they live as shared pure
predicates in protocol/ (see layering section).

v1 prediction scope (decided): movement, inventory browsing, and
simple interactions (open door, pick up). Reconciliation policy on
misprediction (hard snap vs short corrective animation) gets decided
when it first happens in practice.

Prediction depth is hard-limited to ONE unacknowledged command
(decided). Deeper prediction is dishonest in a roguelike — after our
move the world acts, and the client cannot predict monsters, so a
second predicted move would run on state known to be stale — and it
would require rollback/re-simulate machinery. Depth 1 keeps
reconciliation binary: confirmed or snapped, never re-simulated.
Input arriving while a command is unacknowledged is queued
un-predicted (so held-key movement stays continuous, rendered at
authoritative pace); where that queue lives (client vs pipelined to
server) is decided when networking is real.

Spectators require nothing special from the client (decided): a
spectator is a normal client with input disabled. The client already
has to handle events not caused by any local command (most of the
stream is the world acting on its own), and prediction/reconciliation
only trigger on local input — so with no input both are naturally
dormant. Same client code, same event handling.


DECIDED: RNG and determinism
----------------------------

One game RNG, server-side, seeded per game. Enables seeded tournament
races (same dungeon for every entrant). The client may use its own
cosmetic RNG (idle wobble, particles) but it never touches game state.

Replays are event-stream based, not input-replay based — robust across
game-balance changes, since no simulation is re-run.


MILESTONE 0 (done): grid sandbox for camera/look/feel
-----------------------------------------------------

Pre-split scratch code, all in game_main.c: a checkered tile grid and
a player cube stepping tile-to-tile (held keys repeat, 8-dir), camera
following at a semi-topdown pitch. Tunables are defines at the top of
game_main.c (grid size, tile gap/colors, move step time, camera
pitch/distance/fov/follow speed). This exists to lock in the look and
feel before the client/server split; it dissolves into client/ when
milestone 1 starts.


MILESTONE 1 (agreed): one room, walking cube
--------------------------------------------

Protocol message structs + the local message pump + a server that
generates one room and resolves moves + the client walking a cube
around it. Proposed shape, hack on it:

    src/game/protocol/   protocol.h  command/event structs, ids
                         rules.c/h   shared pure predicates
    src/game/server/     server.h    Server_* API
    src/game/client/     client.h    Client_* API
    src/game/game_main.c local pump

meson: protocol_lib (core only), server_lib (core + protocol only —
this is the enforced moat), client + game_main stay in game_lib
(core, platform, engine, protocol).

Local transport = no abstraction at all. game_main pumps once per
frame:

    Client_Update()            input -> predicts -> queues command_t
    Client_PollCommands()      drain client outbox
    Server_HandleCommand()     resolve, world advances
    Server_PollEvents()        drain server outbox
    Client_HandleEvent()       fold into view, reconcile predictions

A future network build replaces the pump with socket code on each
side (and that is where ser/deser lives); client and server code are
untouched. The symmetry lives in the message structs, not in a
transport vtable we don't need yet.

v1 messages (sketch): command_t { type, sequence, union { move {dx,
dy} } }; event_t { type, union { snapshot { extents, terrain cells,
entities, player id }, entity_moved { id, from, to, caused_by_seq },
command_rejected { sequence, reason } } }. Fixed-cap inline arrays
per the struct rules. Terrain/entity ids in protocol.h.


MILESTONE 2 (agreed): monster, FOV, fog of war
----------------------------------------------

A simple monster that wanders the level, plus FOV and fog of war.
This is the milestone where the hidden-information machinery becomes
real: the server computes FOV and only sends visible cells; map
memory (fog of war) is tracked server-side per player and streamed as
"remembered" cell state. The wandering monster exercises the two
things milestone 1 can't: the world acting without any player command
(events not caused by the local client), and entities entering/
leaving the visible set (the client learns of the monster only when
it walks into view, and the server stops telling the client about it
the moment it leaves).


OPEN QUESTIONS
--------------

- Session model: server should think in terms of N attached clients
  per game (1 player + N spectators) even though locally N=1. When do
  we introduce the session/client-slot concept on the server side?

- Client-side smoothing: turn-based state jumps tile-to-tile; the 3d
  view wants short movement/attack animations. Client concern only,
  but affects how events are timestamped/grouped (e.g. "these events
  happened in one world turn" grouping for parallel animation).

- Model/animation format (eventually): leaning OBJ for static meshes
  and Quake-style keyframe vertex animation for movement — one OBJ
  per keyframe (Blender's OBJ export can dump animation as a numbered
  sequence), engine lerps (or snaps, for the chunky 90s look) between
  frames; two vertex buffers + mix factor in the push constant.
  Possibly baked into a small binary blob at build time. Skeletal/
  glTF deliberately avoided: heavy machinery and wrong for the
  aesthetic.

- Replay format: with ser/deser living in the network layer, a replay
  is most naturally the recorded network byte stream. Fine — but it
  means replay recording is a network-layer feature, not available
  until the socket transport exists (or the local transport gains an
  optional record hook that runs the serializer).

- Persistence: save games are server-side state dumps. Format can wait
  until there is state worth saving.

- Directory name bikeshed: protocol/ vs common/. Using protocol/ until
  someone objects.
